post_text: "As a young boy, my family traveled and camped all through the summers, and this travel played a great role in my love for the outdoors. I would watch my mother paint scenes and was fascinated by how she did them. Later in life, I took some lessons from her and I was hooked. Painting scenes that had all been stored-up inside flourished onto the canvas using color to create mood and brought such peace. Art, like music, is a universal language - it can even speak to the very heart and soul in ways my words could never express. I hope my work will bring God's peace to who you are inside." - Steve Wilson of stevewilsonart.com

post_text: ‚ÄúI have been turning wood and creating other wooden items for over 30 years as a hobby. For my turned items I tend to use mostly locally acquired wood. The Bozeman urban forest has quite a variety of tree species, and I‚Äôm always looking for opportunities to collect different types of wood. I‚Äôve discovered that people in this area tend to get quite attached to their trees. When a tree needs to be taken down, what better way to remember it than with a bowl, vessel or turned utensil? It is very exciting to find what is hidden in a log.‚Äù - Jess Tode of Jess Tode Woodworking

Spring is a time when we prepare gardens for new seedlings, clear pots for new flowers, visit farmers‚Äô markets, and enjoy fresh, locally produced fruits, vegetables, meat, dairy, eggs, grains and much more. COVID-19‚Äôs arrival in the United States has created an unprecedented disruption to these seasonal efforts.

When you connect with farmers and buy their goods, you help protect those who rely on sales for their livelihoods and who have already invested in supplies, seed and seasonal operating costs.

Just as there are additional ways for local farmers to reach consumers at this time, there are outlets for you to engage with farmers, establish direct contact, and make your purchases.

Learn more here: https://extension.purdue.edu/article/36596

post_text: Join the SBDC tomorrow in a brief, 30-minute webinar to learn how you can be proactive during the initial stages of COVID-19.
shared_text:
Montana Small Business Development Centers
March 19 at 2:28 PM ¬∑

Tomorrow, the Small Business Webinar Series will present the Business Crisis Toolkit: Control What You Can at 11am. In this brief, 30-minute webinar we are hoping to give business owners some guidance on steps to take during the initial stages of the coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak throughout the country. Established in Missoula, MT in the fall of 2011, Draught Works Brewery was founded on the philosophy of building better beers. This industrial spirit has driven their team to turn out clean, traditional ales and lagers, unique American sours, as well as a wide range of experimental styles. Just as draught is the epitome of fresh beer, the whole Draught Works crew works diligently to guarantee only the highest-quality product, one that reflects our passion for excellence and the spirit of hard work.

*2018 Best of Missoula Winner: Best Brewery
*2019 Best of Missoula Winner: Best Brewery & Best Brew

post_text: Tallow is rich in vitamins A, D, K, and E, and is the main ingredient in Miriam's Inspired Skin Care balms. With 18 different amino acids and a composition of fatty acids that resemble those of our own skin, this balm is antimicrobial, fungicidal, and anti-inflammatory. Blended with native and homegrown herbs like calendula, comfrey, yarrow and rosehip as well as a blend of fragrant essential oils are a dream for dry and cracked skin.

post_text: "With technology so abundant, I think we all secretly long for something more definite and familiar in our lives. When we drink a cup of coffee from pottery we remember it. The way it felt on our lips, how it felt in our hands. We are able to enjoy the vibrant colors, shape, or textures that drew us to the piece in the first place, time and time again." - Laura Viren of Lulu Pottery, Bozeman
